# Frontend rules

Use these rules when implementing the Angular frontend.

Framework:
- Angular 20+.
- Standalone components.
- Signals for local and shared reactive state.
- SCSS for styling.
- Strict TypeScript.

UI language:
- All user-visible text must be Polish.
- Dates should be shown as `DD.MM.YYYY`.
- Currency should use Polish formatting.

Visual direction:
- Base background: cream, approximately `#FAF7EE`.
- Accent: bottle green, approximately `#3F5C3A`.
- Headings: elegant serif such as Cormorant or Playfair.
- Body: clean sans-serif such as Inter or DM Sans.
- Use subtle shadows and soft wedding-planner aesthetics, but keep workflow screens efficient and readable.
- Put visual tokens in `apps/frontend/src/styles/_tokens.scss` once the app scaffold exists.
- Do not hardcode repeated color/font/radius values across components.

UX requirements:
- Build actual working app screens, not a marketing landing page.
- Preserve responsive behavior described in `docs/demo-app/02-frontend.md`.
- Seating drag-and-drop must have a keyboard-accessible fallback.
- Every milestone should ship an end-to-end vertical slice visible in the UI, not only isolated backend or component work.

State and API:
- Prefer small feature services with signals.
- Keep DTOs/types aligned with backend contracts and shared types when `packages/shared-types` exists.
- Handle auth through the SSO token flow described in `wedding-planner-deployment.md`.
